  </nav>

  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Sortation Systems</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Sortation Systems
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A sortation system automatically routes products to many destinations at high speed using scanning data, routing logic, and mechanical sort mechanisms. Sortation systems combine induct conveyors, barcode/RFID scanners, sort conveyors, and destination lanes , managed by warehouse control software , to process 5,000-25,000+ items per hour. The five major sorter types are shoe sorters, pop-up wheel sorters, crossbelt sorters, tilt tray sorters, and bomb bay sorters, each optimized for different product characteristics and throughput requirements.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Shoe Sorters -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="shoe-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Shoe Sorters</div>
      <h2 id="shoe-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Shoe Sorters <span class="text-accent">(Sliding Shoe)</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Shoe sorters (also called sliding shoe sorters) use a flat conveying surface with rows of small divert shoes mounted on slats. The shoes normally align with the direction of travel, forming a smooth surface. When a divert is commanded, actuators beneath the surface slide selected shoes at a 30-45 degree angle, gently pushing the product off the side of the sorter onto the destination lane.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">How Shoe Sorters Work</h3>
        <p>Products ride directly on the shoe surface. A scanner upstream reads the product barcode. The warehouse control system (WCS) determines the destination and calculates when the product will reach the correct sort point. At the right moment, the shoes in that zone activate, creating a diagonal divert path. The shoes contact the product and guide it smoothly off the side at the programmed angle. The product slides down a chute or onto a take-away conveyor at the destination lane.</p>
        <p>Shoe sorters handle flat-bottomed products from 1 to 100 lbs. Typical line speeds: 300-500 FPM. Throughput: 10,000-20,000 sorts per hour. Sort accuracy exceeds 99.5% for properly inducted products. Dematic, Intelligrated (Honeywell), Beumer Group, and KION (Dematic) supply shoe sorter systems.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Current shoe sorter manufacturer brand relationships (Dematic/KION, Intelligrated/Honeywell) -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Shoe Sorter Advantages</h3>
        <p>Shoe sorters provide gentle divert action with minimal product impact. They handle a wide range of product sizes on a common platform. Destination lanes can be on both sides of the sorter (bi-directional sort). No individual carriers are needed , products ride directly on the surface, maximizing sort density. Shoe sorters handle the highest throughput per dollar for flat-bottomed case and carton sorting.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Shoe Sorter Limitations</h3>
        <p>Products must have flat, rigid bottoms to ride on the shoe surface. Polybags, soft packs, and irregularly shaped items may snag on shoe gaps. Very small items (under 6 inches) may slip between shoes. Very light items (under 0.5 lbs) may not respond to shoe contact. For these product types, crossbelt or tilt tray sorters are more reliable.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Pop-Up Wheel Sorters -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="popup-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Pop-Up Wheel Sorters</div>
      <h2 id="popup-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Pop-Up Wheel <span class="text-accent">Sorters</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Pop-up wheel sorters use banks of small, angled wheels mounted between <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller conveyor</a> rollers. When a divert is needed, the wheels pop up above the roller surface and contact the product's bottom. The spinning wheels redirect the product at a 30-45 degree angle onto the destination spur. When not diverting, the wheels retract below the rollers and the product travels straight on the roller surface.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Performance</h3>
        <p>Pop-up wheel sorters handle line speeds up to 600 FPM with products from 1 to 75 lbs. Each pop-up wheel zone serves one destination. Multiple zones along the trunk line each serve a different lane. Throughput: 5,000-15,000 sorts per hour depending on product spacing and number of destinations. Pop-up wheels provide fast activation (0.3-0.5 seconds) for high-speed diverting.</p>
        <p>Pop-up wheel sorters are the most common sortation technology in mid-size distribution centers and <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">packaging facilities</a>. They integrate with standard roller conveyor platforms from Dematic, Intelligrated, Bastian Solutions, and TGW. See our <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/pivot/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">pivot conveyor guide</a> for more on pop-up wheel mechanism details.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Crossbelt Sorters -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="crossbelt-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Crossbelt Sorters</div>
      <h2 id="crossbelt-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Crossbelt <span class="text-accent">Sorters</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Crossbelt sorters use a loop of individual carrier units, each equipped with a short belt conveyor that runs perpendicular (cross) to the main travel direction. Each carrier circulates around the loop at constant speed. Products are inducted onto carriers at induct stations. When a carrier reaches its destination chute, the crossbelt activates and pushes the product off the side into the chute.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Product Versatility</h3>
        <p>Crossbelt sorters handle the widest product range of any sorter type. Small items, polybags, soft packs, tubes, cylinders, irregularly shaped products, and flat items all ride securely on the crossbelt carrier surface. The belt provides positive containment during transport and positive discharge force during sort. Products from 0.1 to 75 lbs and from 3 inches to 36 inches work on standard crossbelt carriers.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">High Throughput</h3>
        <p>Crossbelt sorters achieve 10,000-25,000 sorts per hour. The loop runs at 300-600 FPM. Multiple induct points around the loop maximize carrier utilization. Sort accuracy exceeds 99.9% because each product is positively contained on its carrier , no sliding, no interaction with adjacent products. Beumer Group, Interroll, Dematic, and KNAPP manufacture crossbelt sorter systems.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: KNAPP crossbelt sorter product offering -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Crossbelt Sorter Cost</h3>
        <p>Crossbelt sorters represent the highest capital investment among sorter types. Each carrier is an independent unit with its own belt, motor, and controller. A typical crossbelt loop has 200-1,000 carriers. The per-carrier cost plus the loop infrastructure, induct stations, and controls make crossbelt sorters $$$$ investments. They justify cost in high-volume e-commerce and parcel operations where product variety and sort accuracy requirements are highest.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Tilt Tray and Bomb Bay -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="tilt-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Tilt Tray & Bomb Bay</div>
      <h2 id="tilt-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Tilt Tray & <span class="text-accent">Bomb Bay Sorters</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Tilt Tray Sorters</h3>
        <p>Tilt tray sorters use a loop of individual tray carriers that tilt to one side (left or right) to dump products into destination chutes. Each tray is a flat platform mounted on a pivot. The tray tilts at the destination point, and gravity slides the product off into the chute below. Tilt trays handle products from 0.5 to 50 lbs and suit flat, stable items that stay on the tray during transport without containment.</p>
        <p>Tilt tray sorters provide 8,000-15,000 sorts per hour. They cost less per carrier than crossbelt sorters because the tilt mechanism is simpler than a motorized belt. Tilt trays excel in apparel distribution (folded garments), small parts (cosmetics, electronics), and pharmaceutical order fulfillment. Beumer Group, Dematic, and Crisplant (Beumer) supply tilt tray sorter systems.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Crisplant/Beumer relationship and current product line -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Bomb Bay Sorters</h3>
        <p>Bomb bay sorters (also called trap door sorters) use carriers with a hinged bottom that opens downward to drop products into destination chutes directly below. The carrier travels over the destination position, the doors open, and the product falls into the chute. The doors close and the carrier continues to the induct station for the next product.</p>
        <p>Bomb bay sorters handle products from 0.5 to 30 lbs. They require products that can tolerate a short free-fall drop (6-12 inches). They suit small, durable items: pharmaceutical cartons, cosmetic packages, small electronics, and books. Bomb bay sorters provide 5,000-12,000 sorts per hour and offer compact destination spacing because chutes are directly below the sorter rather than beside it.</p>
        <p>Bomb bay sorters save floor space by stacking destinations vertically (below the sorter loop) rather than spreading them horizontally (alongside the sorter). This makes them the preferred choice in space-constrained facilities with many sort destinations. Dematic and SDI Industries produce bomb bay sorter systems.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: SDI Industries bomb bay sorter product line -->
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Comparison Table -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="comparison-heading">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Comparison</div>
