  <!-- System Components -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="components-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">System Architecture</div>
      <h2 id="components-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Sortation System <span class="text-accent">Components</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Induct system:</strong> The induct system feeds products onto the sorter at controlled spacing and timing. Induct conveyors use <a href="/conveyor-types/flat-belt-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">belt conveyors</a> with gap-creating acceleration zones that singulate products and create uniform spacing. For carrier-based sorters (crossbelt, tilt tray), the induct station loads individual products onto empty carriers. Induct rate limits overall sort throughput , multiple induct points maximize carrier utilization.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Scanning station:</strong> Barcode scanners (laser or camera-based), RFID readers, or vision systems identify each product as it passes the scanning station. The scan provides the routing data (destination) that the control system uses to trigger the sort. Multi-sided scanning arrays (top, side, bottom) read barcodes regardless of label position. Scan rate must match or exceed the sort rate , a missed scan sends the product to a recirculation loop or exception lane.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Sort mechanism:</strong> The sort conveyor itself , the shoe deck, wheel zones, crossbelt loop, or tilt tray loop. The mechanism receives divert commands from the control system and activates at the precise moment the product reaches the destination position.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Destination lanes:</strong> Chutes, take-away conveyors, or accumulation lanes that receive sorted products. Chute destinations use gravity to collect products in bins or gaylords. Conveyor destinations use <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/gravity/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">gravity roller</a> or <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR conveyor</a> lanes for further processing. Destination lane design must handle the peak sort rate without backup , a full destination lane causes sort exceptions.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Recirculation:</strong> Products that cannot sort (full destination, no scan read, exception condition) recirculate back to the scanning station for another attempt. The recirculation loop adds 30-60 seconds per recirculation cycle. High recirc rates reduce effective throughput. System design minimizes recirculation through reliable scanning, adequate destination capacity, and robust routing logic.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Warehouse control software (WCS):</strong> The WCS manages the entire sortation operation: product identification, routing decisions, sort commands, destination management, and exception handling. The WCS interfaces with the warehouse management system (WMS) for order data, carrier data, and shipping information. Dematic, Intelligrated, TGW, and Bastian Solutions provide WCS platforms integrated with their sortation hardware.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="apps-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
      <h2 id="apps-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Sortation <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">E-commerce order fulfillment:</strong> Crossbelt and tilt tray sorters handle the wide product variety in e-commerce operations. Items picked from storage sort to shipping lanes by carrier, shipping method, or geographic zone. The sort handles polybags, mailers, small boxes, and irregularly shaped products that shoe sorters and pop-up wheels cannot.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Parcel and courier distribution:</strong> Shoe sorters and crossbelt sorters handle parcel sorting for last-mile delivery. Parcels sort to destination chutes representing delivery zones, routes, or truck loading positions. Major parcel carriers operate sorters processing 20,000+ parcels per hour. Multiple sorters in a hub handle inbound, outbound, and transfer parcels.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Case sortation for retail distribution:</strong> Shoe sorters and pop-up wheel sorters route cases from receiving to store-specific shipping lanes. Each case scans, and the sorter routes it to the lane assigned to its destination store. Pop-up wheel sorters handle mid-volume retail DCs. Shoe sorters handle high-volume operations with 100+ store lanes.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Pharmaceutical distribution:</strong> Bomb bay and tilt tray sorters handle small pharmaceutical cartons with high accuracy requirements. The positive carrier containment and precise sort accuracy (>99.9%) prevent misdirected medications. Pharmaceutical sortation systems include additional verification scanning at destination lanes.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Packaging line SKU routing:</strong> <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Packaging facilities</a> with many SKUs use pop-up wheel sorters to route finished products to SKU-specific palletizing lanes. Each product scans after case packing, and the sorter routes it to the correct palletizer lane. <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Accumulation zones</a> before sorter induction meter product flow for reliable sorting.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
